ReMap: FYE-101 Task & Email (UG)

Karen West | k.west2@snhu.edu

Publication Date: 2021-03-23

Updated: 2021-03-22

Overview



Theory: The FYE-101 course is a free introductory orientation course designed to help new students familiarize themselves with the learning management system. It is thought that if students log into this free course prior to their first term, they will be more prepared to start classes, and potentially less likely to drop or “melt”.

Hypothesis: Outreaching students to encourage them to log into FYE-101 will improve FYE-101 login rates.

Test Design

Test Metric: FYE-101 Login Rate, calculated as: \[FYE101 Login Rate = \sum_{n=FYE101 Logins} / \sum_{n=Total Registered Students}\]

Testing Groups: Of all eligible members of the population (full criteria list below), control and experiment groups were assigned according to testing cells on the Unify contact.

  • Control Group: 50% received FYE-101 email and task was created on the Unify record
  • Experiment Group: 50% received no emails or tasks

Tasks were created on Tuesday each week during the experiment timeframe and emails were sent at the same time. These treatments only occurred the first week that the student was eligible to receive; they did not occur on a weekly basis.

Experiment Population Eligibility (AKA InPopulation):

  • UG students with a planned term start of 21EW4
  • Student is registered for FYE-101 but has not logged in

Outcomes & Learnings

Overall Results: As of 3/17/21, the FYE-101 Login Rate for the test group was 4.1 percentage points higher (+4.8% change). This difference is statistically significant with a 95% confidence level and two-sided test of proportions.


Learnings:

  • Melt Rate The post-start melt rate for the test group was 1.9 percentage points higher (+2.2% change). This difference is statistically significant with a 95% confidence level and two-sided test of proportions.

Appendix

Interpreting the Results

  • Confidence Level: The percentage of confidence that the result is a consequence of the change made or treatment administered and not a result of random chance. A 95% confidence interval indicates that we are 95% confident the test result is not due to random chance.

  • Statistical Significance: A test result is said to be “statistically significant” when the difference between the results of the test and control groups is too big to have been a result of chance.

  • One-Sided vs. Two-Sided Test A one sided test is used when we only want to prove that the increase in conversions (i.e. the metric) that occurred for the test group is significant; it does not consider whether any decrease in conversions is significant. A two-sided test evaluates the significance of the test group conversions being higher or lower as compared to the control. If we want to be certain that a treatment being tested does not have a negative impact on the metric, then a two-sided test should be conducted.
